quran[42]{c,v,t,f}:
80,1,"He frowned and turned away"
80,2,"that the blind man came to him. {1}",footnotes:1:The style of this first sentence is elegant and subtle. Although in the following sentences the Prophet (peace be upon him) has been directly addressed
80,3,"How could you know? Perhaps he would cleanse himself,"
80,4,"or he might be mindful and good counsel might avail him."
80,5,"Now he who waxes indifferent,"
80,6,"you attend to him,"
80,7,"though you are not to blame if he would not cleanse himself."
80,8,"But he who comes to you running,"
80,9,"and fears (Allah),"
80,10,"you pay no heed to him. {1}",footnotes:1:This is the real point which the Prophet (peace be upon him) had overlooked in the preaching of Islam on that occasion
80,11,"No indeed; {1} this is only a Reminder. {2}",footnotes:1:That is
80,12,"So whoso wills may give heed to it."
80,13,"It is contained in scrolls highly honoured,"
80,14,"most exalted and purified, {1}",footnotes:1:Purified: free from all kinds of mixtures of false ideas and thoughts
80,15,"borne by the hands of scribes,"
80,16,"noble {1} and purified. {2}",footnotes:1:This refers to the angels who were writing the scrolls of the Quran under the direct guidance of Allah
80,17,"Accursed {1} be man! {2} How stubbornly he denies the Truth.",footnotes:1:From here the rebuke turns directly against the disbelievers
80,18,"Out of what did Allah create him?"
80,19,"Out of a sperm-drop {1} did He create him and then determined a measure for him, {2}",footnotes:1:That is
80,20,"and then made the course of life easy for him, {1}",footnotes:1:That is
80,21,"then He caused him to die and brought him to the grave, {1}",footnotes:1:That is
80,22,"and then, whenever He wishes, He will raise him back to life. {1}",footnotes:1:That is
80,23,"Nay, but man did not fulfil what Allah had enjoined upon him. {1}",footnotes:1:He commanded him: Implies the duty that Allah has enjoined on every man in the form of natural guidance as well as the duty to which man’s own existence and every particle of the universe
80,24,"So let man just consider his food: {1}",footnotes:1:That is
80,25,"We poured water, pouring it in great abundance, {1}",footnotes:1:This refers to rainwater. Water vapors are raised in vast quantities from the oceans by the heat of the sun
80,26,"and cleaved the earth, cleaving it asunder; {1}",footnotes:1:Then We split the earth in clefts: Implies cleaving it in a way that the seeds
80,27,"then caused the grain to grow out of it,"
80,28,"together with grapes and vegetables,"
80,29,"and olives and palms,"
80,30,"and dense orchards,"
80,31,"and fruits and pastures –"
80,32,"all this as a provision for you and your cattle. {1}",footnotes:1:That is
80,33,"But when the deafening cry shall be sounded {1}",footnotes:1:The final terrible sounding of the Trumpet at which all dead men shall be resurrected to life.
80,34,"on the Day when each man shall flee from his brother,"
80,35,"and his mother and his father;"
80,36,"and his consort and his children; {1}",footnotes:1:A theme closely resembling to this has already occurred in Surah Al-Maarij
80,37,"on that Day each will be occupied with his own business, making him oblivious of all save himself. {1}",footnotes:1:A tradition has been reported in the Hadith by different methods and through different channels
80,38,"Some faces on that Day shall be beaming with happiness,"
80,39,"and be cheerful and joyous."
80,40,"Some faces on that Day shall be dust-ridden,"
80,41,"enveloped by darkness."
80,42,"These will be the unbelievers, the wicked."
